        {
            "number": 4,
            "revision": "461b3872d49f17428a5d4e8fd3351e86270fa33e",
            "parents": [
                "8841b7d463a5272a87faaa14cb103f778a772770"
            ],
            "ref": "refs/changes/60/72460/4",
            "uploader": {
                "name": "Farah Rasheed",
                "email": "Farah.Rasheed1@dell.com",
                "username": "FarahRasheed1"
            },
            "createdOn": 1720725529,
            "author": {
                "name": "Farah Rasheed",
                "email": "Farah.Rasheed1@dell.com",
                "username": "FarahRasheed1"
            },
            "kind": "NO_CODE_CHANGE",
            "comments": [
                {
                    "file": "/COMMIT_MSG",
                    "line": 12,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Gunnar Mills",
                        "email": "gunnar@gmills.xyz",
                        "username": "gtmills"
                    },
                    "message": "This is a table and a selectall gets all the rows... If we do something special here, this table behaves differently than other tables.."
                },
                {
                    "file": "/COMMIT_MSG",
                    "line": 12,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Farah Rasheed",
                        "email": "Farah.Rasheed1@dell.com",
                        "username": "FarahRasheed1"
                    },
                    "message": "That is indeed correct...this change was more to protect against the root user being disabled/deleted unintentionally in case there are a lot of users in the list and the user does the \"select all\" and proceeds to delete/disable all of them. If the root is unselected, the user has a second chance to delete/disable the root if that was their intent after the previous operation has completed."
                },
                {
                    "file": "/COMMIT_MSG",
                    "line": 12,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Farah Rasheed",
                        "email": "Farah.Rasheed1@dell.com",
                        "username": "FarahRasheed1"
                    },
                    "message": "@Gunnar, any more thoughts on this?"
                },
                {
                    "file": "/COMMIT_MSG",
                    "line": 12,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Gunnar Mills",
                        "email": "gunnar@gmills.xyz",
                        "username": "gtmills"
                    },
                    "message": "I don't agree with this design, I don't think this table should be any differnet. That said, I appear to be the only one. I've give until Monday then will  +2."
                },
                {
                    "file": "/COMMIT_MSG",
                    "line": 12,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Nikhil Ashoka",
                        "email": "a.nikhil@ibm.com",
                        "username": "Nikhil-Ashoka"
                    },
                    "message": "I agree with Gunnar, we already have confirm dialog implementation for \"delete\", Can we implement the same for \"disable\" operation instead of overriding the \"select all\" operation. Thoughts?"
                },
                {
                    "file": "/COMMIT_MSG",
                    "line": 12,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Farah Rasheed",
                        "email": "Farah.Rasheed1@dell.com",
                        "username": "FarahRasheed1"
                    },
                    "message": "A couple things:\n\n1. Yes, adding a confirmation dialog for disable is certainly an option. I can get on board with that if others agree.\n\n2. The individual row for root user has the \"delete\" icon disabled. I have been wary of seeing what happens if the user selects all the users and deletes them. Does the backend process the request to delete the root user or simply ignore it? If the backend processes the request to delete the root user, and the individual row had delete icon disabled, doesn't it stand to reason that the same should apply from the table checkbox itself?\n3. The whole idea is to not allow the root user to be deleted (or should we allow the root to be deleted, is there a spec point regarding this?). We protected against that happening by disabling the delete icon on the root user row, now it is a question of not allowing it through other means on the GUI."
                },
                {
                    "file": "/COMMIT_MSG",
                    "line": 12,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Gunnar Mills",
                        "email": "gunnar@gmills.xyz",
                        "username": "gtmills"
                    },
                    "message": "> Yes, adding a confirmation dialog for disable is certainly an option. I can get on board with that if others agree.\n\nI would prefer that.."
                },
                {
                    "file": "/COMMIT_MSG",
                    "line": 12,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Farah Rasheed",
                        "email": "Farah.Rasheed1@dell.com",
                        "username": "FarahRasheed1"
                    },
                    "message": "Done.\n\nThough it is a definite improvement, I am still a little wary that it is a tad easy to miss this when there are a hundred plus users in the table and users can select all of them and delete/disable them (even with a confirmation modal) before realizing what they did."
                }
            ],
